    Q : internal working of hashset?
    ans : 1 : HashSet relies on a HashMap to store elements, where the elements are stored as keys, and a dummy 
	          value (like PRESENT) is used as the value.	
		  2 : When adding an element, HashSet uses the element's hashCode() to find the appropriate bucket.
				-> If the bucket already has elements (collision), equals() checks for duplicates. 
		  3 : so overall when you write s.add(10); it internally calls hashmap map.put() method which return 
              answer in boolean if value comes for first time than add the value (true) and if the value comes
              second time same than it will return false.
		  4 : When a collision happens in a HashSet, internally in the HashMap, a LinkedList is formed to store multiple 
		      elements in the same bucket.	  
            set.add(10);// it internally calls hashmap method map.put 
			
			public boolean add(E e){// here e is value like 10
			    return map.put(e,present)==null;
			}
             
        or 

HashSet internally uses a HashMap.
Whenever we add an element, HashSet calculates its hashcode and finds a bucket.
Inside that bucket, it checks with equals() to make sure the element is not already present.
If it’s a duplicate, it is not added.
If it’s new, HashSet stores it as a key in the internal HashMap with a dummy value.
This is why HashSet is fast and does not allow duplicates.”
Yes, HashSet forms a LinkedList inside the same bucket when two elements get the same bucket number using hashCode(). Because internally HashSet uses a HashMap, and HashMap stores collided elements in a LinkedList.”


        or

        HashSet uses HashMap internally.
		It puts elements as keys in buckets using hashcode.
		It checks duplicates using equals().
		That’s why HashSet doesn’t allow duplicate values and is very fast.
		equals() checks if the item is already inside.
        If yes → skip.
        If no → add.”


