Q24 : Internal working of HashMap ? 
Ans : Explain this in interview : 
      Map stores elements as key-value pair we use put method to insert key-value pair.
      Internally map uses an array of bucket to store elements. Each element of array is known as 
      Bucket. Bucket contains node, node contains 4 things hashcode, key,value,	and next node 
	  address.To calculate Bucket index we use hashcode on key with bucket length to get bucket
      index on which bucket index the data should be stored. suppose we have bucket length of 16
	  which is actually a by default length of the array of bucket.if the load factor crosses 75% 
	  than means total we have 16 buckets and we have filled 12 bucket which is 75% of 16 so now 
      buckets will be resize doubled to 32.
      
	  This is for understanding what it uses internally : 
	  
      Hashing : Hashing is the process of converting an object into integer by using the method 
                hashcode.
      equals : equals methods is used to check wheather two objects are equal or not. this is 
                provided by object class. 
      
      Bucket :bucket is an element of HashMap array is used to store nodes.
	          array has bucket and bucket has nodes. 
              node consist  4 things : hash value , key , value , next node address or null.
             			 
	  Collision : When two key points the same the bucket index, this is called collision. 
      
	  Each bucket can hold multiple entries in the form of a linked list or a tree structure.
	  
      There are two Scenerios : 
      1 : here equals method is used to compare keys. If both key are same older value 
          will be replaced by new value
      2 : If u got the same bucket index but keys are not equals then new node is added to 
	      previous node at the same bucket index .

	      or

	  “In HashMap, if two keys have the same hash and equals() returns true, the old value is replaced. But if equals() returns false, HashMap creates a new node in the same bucket using a LinkedList (or Tree).    
       
Internal HashMap Index Calculation & Collision Handling
🔹 1. Index Formula:
index = (hashCode(key) & (n - 1))
n = current capacity of the HashMap (e.g., 16 by default)

& - ensures the index is always within array bounds.

🔹 2. If key is null:
HashMap allows one null key.

It is always stored in bucket at index 0(1st bucket).

🔹 3. Collision Handling:
If multiple keys land in the same bucket, they are first stored as a linked list.

If the number of nodes in that bucket exceeds 8 (TREEIFY_THRESHOLD), and the capacity is at least 64,
 the linked list is converted into a balanced binary tree (BST) to speed up lookup.
 
 
